# Java Basics - The Complete Curriculum

## 1. Introduction to Java
Java is a high-level, class-based, object-oriented programming language designed to have as few implementation dependencies as possible. It is a general-purpose programming language intended to let application developers *write once, run anywhere* (WORA).

## 2. JDK, JRE, JVM
These three form the backbone of Java development:
- **JVM (Java Virtual Machine)**: An abstract machine that enables your computer to run a Java program.
- **JRE (Java Runtime Environment)**: Includes the JVM and core libraries required to run Java applications.
- **JDK (Java Development Kit)**: The full kit for developers. It includes the JRE plus development tools like compilers (javac) and debuggers.

## 3. Variables & Data Types
Java is strongly typed. Every variable must have a declared type.

### Primitives:
- `int` (numbers)
- `double` (decimals)
- `boolean` (true/false)
- `char` (single character)

### Non-Primitives:
- `String`
- `Arrays`
- Classes

```java
int age = 25;
String name = "Alex";
boolean isJavaFun = true;
```

## 4. Operators
- **Arithmetic**: `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`
- **Relational**: `==`, `!=`, `>`, `<`
- **Logical**: `&&` (AND), `||` (OR), `!` (NOT)
- **Assignment**: `=`, `+=`, `-=`

## 5. Control Statements
Direct the flow of execution based on conditions.

```java
if (age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Vote");
} else {
    System.out.println("Wait");
}
```

- `if-else`
- `switch-case`

## 6. Loops
Repeat code blocks multiple times.

```java
// For Loop
for(int i=0; i<5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}

// While Loop
while(condition) {
    // code
}
```

## 7. Arrays
Store multiple values of the same type in a single variable.

```java
String[] cars = {"Volvo", "BMW", "Ford"};
System.out.println(cars[0]); // Outputs Volvo
```

## 8. Methods
A block of code which only runs when it is called. Used to reuse code.

```java
static void myMethod() {
    System.out.println("I just got executed!");
}
```

## 9. Class & Object
- **Class**: A blueprint (template) for creating objects.
- **Object**: An instance of a class.

```java
class Car {
    String color = "red";
}

Car myCar = new Car(); // Object creation
```

## 10. Constructor
A special method used to initialize objects. The constructor is called when an object of a class is created.

```java
public class Main {
    int x;
    public Main() {
        x = 5;
    }
}
```

## 11. Inheritance
One class (child) acquires the properties and methods of another class (parent) using `extends` keyword.

```java
class Vehicle { ... }
class Car extends Vehicle { ... }
```

## 12. Polymorphism (Basic)
Polymorphism means "many forms". It occurs when we have many classes that are related to each other by inheritance.
- Method Overloading (Compile-time)
- Method Overriding (Run-time)

## 13. Encapsulation
Bundling data (variables) and methods together.
- Use `private` variables.
- Use `public` getter and setter methods to access/update them.

## 14. Abstraction (Intro)
Hiding internal details and showing only functionality.
- **Abstract Class**: Cannot be instantiated.
- **Interface**: A completely "abstract class".

## 15. String Handling
Strings in Java are objects, not primitive types.

```java
String txt = "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ";
System.out.println("Length: " + txt.length());
System.out.println(txt.toUpperCase());
```

## 16. Exception Handling (Basic)
Managing errors gracefully using `try`, `catch`, and `finally`.

```java
try {
    int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3};
    System.out.println(numbers[10]); // Error!
} catch (Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Something went wrong.");
}
```

## 17. Basic Programs

### Factorial Program
```java
int fact=1;
int number=5;
for(int i=1;i<=number;i++){
    fact=fact*i;
}
System.out.println("Factorial: "+fact);
```

### Fibonacci Series
```java
int n1=0,n2=1,n3,i,count=10;
System.out.print(n1+" "+n2);
for(i=2;i<count;++i) {
    n3=n1+n2;
    System.out.print(" "+n3);
    n1=n2;
    n2=n3;
}
```

# Java Advanced - Master the Art

## Introduction to Advanced Java

In the Java Advanced course, you will learn all the concepts that will make you a professional-level Java developer. This course focuses on advanced aspects of Object-Oriented Programming, Collections Framework, Exception Handling, and Multithreading.

## Part 1: Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)

### 1.1 Classes and Objects

A Class is a blueprint from which objects are created.

public class Student {
    // Instance variables
    private String name;
    private int rollNo;
    private double gpa;

    // Constructor
    public Student(String name, int rollNo, double gpa) {
        this.name = name;
        this.rollNo = rollNo;
        this.gpa = gpa;
    }

    // Methods
    public void displayInfo() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name);
        System.out.println("Roll No: " + rollNo);
        System.out.println("GPA: " + gpa);
    }

    // Getters
    public String getName() {
        return name;
    }
}
